    </p>

    <h2>Types of Maryland Divorce We Handle</h2>

    <h3>Contested Divorce in Maryland</h3>
    <p>
      A contested divorce occurs when spouses cannot agree on one or more key issues — including asset division, spousal support, child custody, or child support. These cases require full litigation before a Maryland Circuit Court judge. Our attorneys are skilled litigators who prepare meticulously for every hearing and trial, ensuring your position is presented as powerfully as possible.
    </p>
    <p>
      Contested divorces require careful strategy from day one. We analyze the facts, anticipate opposing arguments, and build a comprehensive legal position designed to protect your most important interests.
    </p>

    <h3>Uncontested Divorce in Maryland</h3>
    <p>
      When both parties can agree on all material issues — including property division, spousal support, and (if applicable) child custody and support — Maryland law allows for a streamlined uncontested divorce process. Our attorneys help you negotiate, draft, and finalize a comprehensive settlement agreement that covers every critical detail and protects both parties.
    </p>
    <p>
      Even in seemingly amicable situations, having experienced legal counsel review your agreement is essential. We ensure no critical provisions are overlooked and that the agreement is drafted in a way that will hold up long-term.
    </p>

    <h2>Maryland Grounds for Divorce</h2>
    <p>Maryland law recognizes two grounds for absolute divorce:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Mutual Consent:</strong> Both parties agree to the divorce and have resolved all issues (requires no separation period).</li>
      <li><strong>6-Month Separation:</strong> Spouses have lived separate and apart without cohabitation for at least 6 months continuously.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Our attorneys will evaluate which pathway makes the most strategic sense for your case and guide you through the process step by step.
    </p>

    <h2>The Divorce Process in Maryland</h2>
    <p>A Maryland divorce typically involves the following stages:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Filing a Complaint for Absolute Divorce</strong> in the appropriate Circuit Court</li>
      <li><strong>Service of process</strong> on the opposing party</li>
      <li><strong>Discovery</strong> (financial disclosure, interrogatories, depositions)</li>
      <li><strong>Negotiation</strong> and settlement attempts</li>
      <li><strong>Trial</strong> (if settlement is not reached)</li>
      <li><strong>Divorce Decree</strong> entered by the court</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Throughout this process, our attorneys apply the <strong>PROMISE Framework™</strong> to ensure you are strategically prepared at every stage.
    </p>

    <h2>Key Issues in Maryland Divorce</h2>
    <p>Maryland divorce proceedings address a range of critical family law issues, including:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/asset-division" class="text-teal-600 hover:underline">Asset and debt division</a> — equitable distribution of marital property</li>
      <li><a href="/spousal-support" class="text-teal-600 hover:underline">Spousal support</a> — temporary and permanent alimony</li>
      <li><a href="/child-custody" class="text-teal-600 hover:underline">Child custody</a> — legal and physical custody arrangements</li>
      <li>Child support — calculation under Maryland Child Support Guidelines</li>
      <li><a href="/high-net-worth-divorce" class="text-teal-600 hover:underline">High-asset considerations</a> — retirement accounts, real estate, investments</li>
    </ul>

